-- Japan, China, India and Malaysia: Asian Local Bonds and Currency Previews
-- B y   A n d r e a   W o n g
-- 2010-10-12T22:13:08Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-12/japan-china-india-and-malaysia-asian-local-bonds-and-currency-previews.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Machinery orders fell 3.9 percent in August from
July, when they rose 8.8 percent, according to a survey of
economists. The Cabinet Office will release the report at 8:50
a.m. in Tokyo.  The yield on the 0.8 percent government bond due September
2020 was at 0.85 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co.,
the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 81.79 per dollar at 7:06 a.m. in Tokyo.  China: The finance ministry will sell at least 28 billion
yuan ($4.2 billion) of seven-year bonds.  The government will probably say tomorrow export growth
slowed to 26 percent in September from a year earlier, after a
34.4 percent increase in August, according to a Bloomberg News
survey of economists.  The yield on the 2.53 percent note due June 2015 was 2.87
percent. The yuan was at 6.6734.  India: The government will sell 40 billion rupees (896
million) of 91-day bills and 20 billion rupees of 182-day debt
today.  The yield on the 7.8 percent bond due May 2020 was 8.01
percent. The rupee was at 44.67 per dollar.  Malaysia: The central bank will sell 3 billion ringgit
($968 million) of 67-day bills and 1 billion ringgit of 364-day
notes. It will also sell 1 billion ringgit of 91-day Islamic
debt.  The yield on the 3.835 percent bond due August 2015 was
3.27 percent. The ringgit was at 3.0988.  To contact the reporters on this story:
